04728nam a22007935i 9781442606746DE-B159720200623100627.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200623t20202009onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814426067467 a10.3138/97814426067462doi  a(DE-B1597)551298  a(OCoLC)1163879125  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aB722.F8bJ43 2009eb 7aHIS0370102bisacsh04a378.44/51242221 aJeauneau, Edouard, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRethinking the School of Chartres /cEdouard Jeauneau. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2020] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (136 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aRethinking the Middle Ages00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tAbbreviations -- tForeword -- tChapter 1. The School of Chartres: Myth or Reality? -- tChapter 2. Fulbert of Chartres: The Mythical Founder of the School of Chartres -- tChapter 3. Bernard of Chartres: "The Foremost Platonist of Our Time" -- tChapter 4. William of Conches: "The Most Accomplished Grammarian after Bernard of Chartres" -- tChapter 5. Gilbert de la Porrée: Chancellor of Chartres and Demanding Master -- tChapter 6. Thierry of Chartres: "The Most Devoted Explorer of the Liberal Arts" -- tChapter 7. John of Salisbury: From Disciple of William of Conches to Bishop of Chartr -- tChapter 8. In Lieu of a Conclusion -- tNotes -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn this brief essay, esteemed medieval historian Edouard Jeauneau examines a much-debated question in medieval intellectual history: did the famous School of Chartres actually exist? Gracefully acknowledging the suggestion by Sir Richard Southern in 1965 that the School was actually a myth, Jeauneau argues that the School did in fact exist but perhaps was not as important as previously thought. Jeauneau provides a fascinating portrait of the School of Chartres during its heyday in the first half of the twelfth century, bringing to light the accomplishments of Fulbert of Chartres, Bernard of Chartres, Thierry of Chartres, Gilbert of Poitiers and William of Conches. Deftly translated by Claude Paul Desmarais, Rethinking the School of Chartres provides a narrative that is critical, passionate, and witty. Sixteen black-and-white images are included. This is the third title in a series called Rethinking the Middle Ages, which is committed to re-examining the Middle Ages, its themes, institutions, people, and events with short studies that will provoke discussion among students and medievalists, and invite them to think about the middle ages in new and unusual ways. The series editor, Paul Edward Dutton, invites suggestions and submissions.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jun 2020) 0aEducation, MedievalzFrancezChartres. 0aFrance - Vie intellectuelle - 987-1515. 4aBernard of Chartres. 4aCoursebook. 4aFulbert of Chartres. 4aGilbert of Poitiers. 4aSchool of Chartres. 4aSir Richard Southern. 4aThierry of Chartres. 4aWilliam of Conche. 4amedieval intellectual history. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh1 aDesmarais, Claude 08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311049095440uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144260674640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442606746423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442606746.jpg  a978-3-11-049095-4  University of Toronto Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK